## Joel Greenblatt's Magic Formula

Joel Greenblatt's book "The Little Book That (Still) Beats the Market" describes a _magic formula_ that has been backtested (over decades) to produce above market returns - if applied for periods of 10 years or more.  

The main idea behind the magic formula is to invest in businesses that are:  
  - efficiently turning over a profit (using _return on capital_ calculation) AND,
  - being priced at a discount (using _earnings yield_ calculation) 

Note that all these calculations are done on the past (most recent) financial data.  

### Return on Capital

Return on Capital measures the $earnings per $1 of capital invested by the business. This measures how efficiently the busines is turning a profit  

Greenblatt argues that businesses with an edge should expect a high ROC.  

  > Return on Capital = EBITDA / (Net Working Capital + Net Fixed Assets)

  where 
  > _Net Working Capital_ = current assets - current liabilities,    
  > _Net Fixed Assets_, AKA Net Property Plant & Equipment

### Earnings Yield

Earnings Yield measures the $earnings per $1 of investment. The higher the better. Think of it as a % of return - i.e. If I invested $x in this company, I expect to yield y% per year.  

We obtain a hedge/margin of safety against unknown risks when we buy a good business (return on capital) that is being offered at a discounted (relatively speaking) price.  

The higher the earnings yield, the more margin of safety.  

  > Earnings Yield = EBITDA / Enterprise Value

  where  
  > Enterprise Value is _market capitlization of the company + total debt - cash, cash equivalents_ - this basically measures how much it takes to buy the company (since buying it would require paying out all share holder equities, and also the debts on the business, less any cash, cash equivalents that can be used to offset the outlays)

### $AAPL

```
ROC = EBITDA / (Net Working Capital + Net Fixed Assetes)
    = 85.16B / (38,321,000,000 + 36,766,000,000)
    = 85.16B / 75,087,000,000
    = 1.134

i.e. $1.134 per $1 of company capital deployed

Earnings Yield = EBITDA / Enterprise Value
               = 85.16B / 2.29T
               = 0.037

i.e. $0.037 per $1 invested, or 3.7% return per $1 invested...
```

### $AMD

```
Return on Capital = EBITDA / (Net Working Capital + Net Fixed Assets)
                  = 1,680,000,000 / ((3,726,000 + 849,000) x 1,000)
                  = 1,680,000,000 / (4,575,000 x 1,000)
                  = 0.367

i.e. company earned $0.367 per $1 of company capital deployed

Earnings Yield = EBITDA / Enterprise Value
               = 1,680,000,000 / 101,740,000,000
               = 0.0165

i.e. $0.0165 per $1 invested, or 1.65% per $1 invested...
```

### $INTC (NYSE / Intel Corp)

Earnings Yield = EBITDA / Enterprise Value
